{{Infobox book | italic title = (see above) | name = Modern Operating Systems | image = Modern Operating Systems.jpg| image_size = | caption = | alt = | author = [[Andrew S. Tanenbaum]], Herbert Bos | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English, German | series = Learning | subject = covers current [[UNIX]]® standards (POSIX.1-2001 /SUSv3 and POSIX.1-2008 /SUSv4 ) | genre = | published = 2nd Edition 2011 ([[Prentice Hall]], Inc.) 4th Edition March 20, 2014 ([[Pearson PLC]]) | media_type = | pages = 1101 | awards = | isbn = 978-0133591620 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | wikisource = | exclude_cover = }} [[File:Simplified Structure of the Linux Kernel.svg|thumb|Page 851: Simplified illustration of the structure of the [[Linux kernel]].]] '''''Modern Operating Systems''''' is a book written by [[Andrew S. Tanenbaum|Andrew Tanenbaum]], a version (which does not target implementation) of his book ''[[Operating Systems: Design and Implementation]]''. It is now in its 4th edition, published March 2014 ({{ISBN|0-13-359162-X}}).
''Modern Operating Systems'' (mostly known as ''MOS'') is a popular book across the globe and includes the fundamentals of an [[operating system]] with small amounts of code written in autonomous [[C (programming language)|C language]]. ''MOS'' describes many [[scheduling algorithm]]s.
